COMPONENT NAME: LKM MSSQL to MSSQL (BCP)
AUTHOR: Oracle
Description: - Loading Knowledge Module - Loads data from a Microsoft SQL Server to a Microsoft SQL Server database using the BCP utility. - A view is created on the source server and a temporary table is created on the target server. - When using this module on a journalized source table, the Journaling table is first updated to flag the records consumed and then cleaned from these records at the end of the interface.
Restrictions: - Source and Work Databases must be set to 'select into/bulk copy' option. - Execution can be blocked when the file generated by bcp is empty. - The option DEFAULT_DIRECTORY indicates the location of the temporary generated file. It must be accessible by both Sunopsis Agent and the Miscrosoft SQL Server instance and should not contain whitespaces. UNC paths (ex: //machine_name/share_directory/...) are supported but decrease performances. - Sunopsis Agent must have BCP installed. - The option BCP_DIRECTORY indicates the location of the BCP program. - For performance reasons, it is recommanded to install Sunopsis Agent either on the Source or on the Target Server.
Call command to execute a shell
Enter the name of the command shell specific processor. Examples: - On Windows: DB2CMD /c /w OR cmd.exe /c - On Unix / Linux: sh -c OR db2cmd -c -w
Enter the name of the command shell specific processor. Examples: - On Windows: DB2CMD /c /w OR cmd.exe /c - On Unix / Linux: sh -c OR db2cmd -c -w
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
Temp. Directory for the data file

Directory where the temporary data file is created. This directory must be a valid path on the machine running the Sunopsis Agent. Examples: - On Windows: D:\MyDatafiles\MyTemporaryFolder - On Unix / Linux: /usr/tmp
Directory where the BCP program is installed on the agent's machine. E.g. C:\"Program Files"\"Microsoft SQL Server"\90\Tools\Binn\

Set this option to Yes to load data (export/import) in Unicode character format.
- The target Oracle database must support Unicode - Make sure column width is sufficient at target datastore for a column to hold Unicode content.
